# Reversion-clause discipline

When the disposition for a question is "we don't need this now," the
right shape is not "refused forever" and not "kept open for future
flexibility." It is **rejected now, with explicit named criteria
under which the rejection reverts to a positive decision.**

The discipline applies at every altitude where a decision rejects
optionality. Without a name, it gets re-derived under pressure each
time the pattern recurs; with a name, design rounds and review
cycles can reach for the shape directly.

## Where the pattern appears

The discipline is in active use across at least five altitudes of
Shekyl's decision-making:

- **Type-derivation.** A `derive(Clone)` rejected because no caller
  needs it. **Landed:** `AllKeysBlob`
  (`rust/shekyl-crypto-pq/src/account.rs` §"Not Clone"). **Planned
  (V3.0 / Cluster 2 PR A):** `HybridSecretKey` and the remaining
  Cluster 2.5 Classification-C Hybrid types, per the `Hybrid*` secret
  types entry in `docs/FOLLOWUPS.md`'s V3.0 queue — the AllKeysBlob
  Not-Clone shape is the canonical template these types adopt when
  the work lands. Reopened in any of these cases if a caller emerges,
  with documented justification, not by reflex re-derivation.
- **Feature shape.** An encrypted-persistence opt-in rejected at
  V3.0 (`docs/design/STAGE_1_PR_4_REFRESH_ENGINE.md` §5.4.8 #1 F1
  R17 hardening); reopened conditional on demonstrated need +
  threat-model review + `AUDIT_SCOPE.md` amendment. The encrypted
  RPC cache rejection at F7 carries the same shape.
- **Design-round closure.** A round closed (PR 5 §7 closure rule);
  reopened only on substrate findings, not sequential numbering. A
  substrate-completeness amendment is not a new round; an under-
  specification surfaced post-closure does not reopen the round it
  belonged to but is named explicitly as a post-closure pin.
- **Work-item placement.** A FOLLOWUPS item rejected from V3.0
  (`docs/FOLLOWUPS.md` §"V3.0 pre-genesis queue"); reopened if
  rechecking surfaces "this still needs to land before genesis."
  Structural deferral V3.0 → V3.1+ requires explicit decision and
  brief rationale, not silent migration.
- **Inherited-architecture migration.** A deferral rejected as
  cost-benefit-defer-to-later anti-pattern
  (`16-architectural-inheritance.mdc` §"The 'cost-benefit-defer-to-
  later' anti-pattern"); reopened only on genuinely-prohibitive
  cost (multi-quarter scope; cross-component coordination breaking
  the discipline budget).

## Why the shape

Optionality without concrete need is **debt, not flexibility.** Pre-
provisioning for hypothetical callers, hypothetical attack surfaces,
or hypothetical reviewers spreads attack surface and review-attention
cost forever to handle states that may never occur. Speculative
extensibility is the failure mode that loads `[[deprecated]]`
annotations without target versions (`15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`'s
"FOLLOWUPS.md is not a graveyard"), accumulates `Clone` derives that
no caller uses, and shapes APIs around imagined future consumers
instead of actual current ones.

Refusal-forever is the other failure: it commits the project to
positions whose justifications may dissolve as the substrate
changes. M3d Finding 5 caught exactly this — `TransferDetails`'
non-`Clone` rationale ("`Zeroizing` second allocation the compiler
can't track") was load-bearing under the pre-M3d schema; M3d's
substrate change made the rationale vacuous; the discipline
survived but needed re-anchoring. A rule whose disposition is
"refuse forever" with no reopening clause cannot re-anchor when
its substrate shifts; it either survives by accident (the discipline
still makes sense under the new substrate, by coincidence) or
becomes residual drift (the discipline persists as a vestigial
constraint nobody can justify).

The reversion clause threads the needle: the current state's
disposition is fixed by current criteria; the future state's
disposition is conditional on named, substrate-anchored criteria.
Substrate change triggers re-evaluation; substrate stasis preserves
the disposition. The discipline neither over-commits (pre-
provisioning) nor under-commits (refusing-forever).

## The shape itself

A reversion-clause-shaped disposition records three things:

1. **The rejection.** What is being rejected and why under current
   conditions. Cite the substrate and the criteria that drive the
   rejection.
2. **The reopening criteria.** What specific, observable, substrate-
   anchored change would trigger re-evaluation. "If we ever need X"
   is not a criterion; "if a production caller emerges that requires
   X" is. "If circumstances change" is not a criterion; "if the
   ml-dsa upstream crate's API is structurally incompatible with
   `from_zeroizing`" is.
3. **The re-evaluation shape.** What the re-evaluation looks like —
   a new design round, a doc-comment update, a rules amendment, an
   `AUDIT_SCOPE.md` addition, a threat-model review, a fresh
   per-trait PR's pre-flight, etc. The shape names who decides and
   what evidence they need. "Reopen if needed" is not a re-evaluation
   shape; "Reopen via design-round 1 of the per-trait PR following
   the §6 readiness gate" is.

The discipline does *not* require predicting future state; it
requires naming what the current substrate is and what kind of
substrate-change would matter. A reversion clause without a named
substrate-change-class is equivalent to "we'll think about it
later" and fails the discipline.

## Anti-patterns

- **"Keep it for flexibility."** Optionality without a named caller
  is debt. If you can't name the reopening criteria, the disposition
  is reject-with-no-reopening-clause (delete-now per
  `15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`'s default).
- **"Refuse forever."** Disposition without reopening criteria is
  brittle to substrate change. If the substrate shifts and the
  refusal's rationale dissolves, the refusal becomes residual drift
  rather than load-bearing discipline.
- **"The audits keep coming back clean, so we can relax the
  check."** The audits come back clean because the discipline is
  continuous; relaxing the check is the failure mode that produces
  the next audit's discovery (per `16-architectural-inheritance.mdc`
  §"The 'audits-are-clean-so-compress' anti-pattern"). The
  reopening criterion for relaxing a discipline check is *not*
  "the discipline has been working"; it is a substrate-anchored
  reason the discipline is no longer load-bearing.
- **"We'll think about it later."** "Later" without named criteria
  is indefinite. The reversion clause must be specific enough that
  a future maintainer can determine, without re-deriving the
  original reasoning, whether the criteria have been met.
- **"Reopen on request."** Disposition that allows reopening on
  the request of any future commit-author is no discipline at all;
  the reopening criteria must be substrate-anchored, not author-
  preference-anchored.

## Recurrence pattern

The discipline's failure mode is the same shape regardless of
altitude: a disposition that should be reject-now-with-reopening-
criteria gets recorded as either pre-provision-for-flexibility
(too lax; debt accumulates) or refuse-forever (too tight; brittle
to substrate change). Both failures are caught by the same
question: **"if the substrate that drives this disposition shifts,
what would re-trigger evaluation?"** If the answer is "nothing
in particular" the disposition is refuse-forever and should be
reshaped. If the answer is "any future contributor's preference"
the disposition is pre-provision-for-flexibility and should be
tightened.

This is the question every reject-disposition should be paired
with at write time, not at review time. By review time, the
reviewer may not have the substrate context to validate the
reopening criteria; the author does.

## Related rules

- **`15-deletion-and-debt.mdc`** — the work-item disposition
  altitude. "FOLLOWUPS items have target versions; items without
  get one within 30 days or are closed as 'won't fix'" is the
  reversion-clause discipline applied to deferred work. The "When
  to use `[[deprecated]]`" rule is its application to API surfaces.
- **`16-architectural-inheritance.mdc`** — the architectural-
  disposition altitude. The cost-benefit-defer-to-later anti-pattern
  is the negative form; the architectural-integrity-now disposition
  is the positive form's application to migration decisions. The
  "audits-are-clean-so-compress" anti-pattern is the reversion-
  clause failure applied to discipline maintenance.
- **`17-dependency-discipline.mdc`** — the dependency-recommendation
  altitude. Recommendations are not reopened on training-data
  recall; they are re-verified at source when the substrate
  (workspace version, feature flags, audit posture) changes. The
  rule's verification cadence is a reversion-clause shape — the
  "good for the version's lifetime" disposition has named substrate-
  change triggers.
- **`19-validation-surface-discipline.mdc`** — the bundling-
  decision altitude. The reversion criterion for bundling is whether
  the validation surfaces have collapsed; substrate change (a new
  reviewer-facing property emerging) triggers re-evaluation.
- **`00-mission.mdc`** — the priority-hierarchy altitude. When a
  reject-disposition cites the priority hierarchy, the reopening
  criterion is typically "substrate-change that re-orders the
  priority calculus" rather than "preference-change that re-orders
  the priority calculus." The priority hierarchy is the substrate;
  preferences are not.
